snippet.textDisplay:
Very nice video and all explanations make sense.  Great work!

On the thoracic spine floor rotation with the rod it is difficult to keep your hips on the floor, hence I believe "All fours torso rotation" exercise is more effective. Especially when you take away arms momentum by keeping your fingers at your temple. This isolated rotation will address the mid back mobility while keeping lumbar spine safe and sound.

Serious question now, Jeff:


You have produced an unbelievable number of high quality videos explaining why why moves are sub-optimal and what can be done to improve or replace them. As part of my exercise regime I do a couple of circuit training/cross-fit style classes each week; I enjoy the energy and the semi-competitive environment helps me go that extra mile. Occasional, however, one of these bad boys will turn up. Do you have any advice on how to inform the instructor that this move is (worst case) damaging or (more usually) not doing what it is supposed to, in a non-critical and positive way? Or should I even bother, given than some instructors can be quite egotistical (and nobody appreciates unsolicited advice)? Would it just be better to alter my own movements to fit with your videos and screw everyone else over?


I know this basically boils down to assertiveness techniques but you may have been in similar situations before...
